tendersummary="The first 10 pages of the document provide a range of information regarding the regulations, fees, bidding process, contact details, and interpretation of terms. The document starts with a table listing various regulations, sections, and subsections mentioned throughout the document. It then provides a context and summary of the tender document, including the title, purpose, and issuing authority. The document also includes a disclaimer, stating that SECI reserves the right to modify the document and that it is prepared in good faith.\n\nThe pages also outline the bidding process and fees associated with the Request for Selection (RfS) for the supply of 1000 MW of firm and dispatchable power. It mentions a document fee, bid processing fee, earnest money deposit, and performance bank guarantee. The page provides the date, time, and venue of the pre-bid meeting, as well as the deadlines for bid submission and the e-Reverse Auction (e-RA).\n\nContact information for SECI and ISN-ETS is provided for any assistance required. Bidders are reminded to comply with the RfS documents and can download the complete document from the ISN-ETS Portal or SECI website. Clarifications and amendments will also be available on these websites.\n\nThe document then explains the objective of the bidding process, which is to provide firm and dispatchable renewable energy power to Distribution Companies (DISCOMs) through renewable energy sources. It highlights SECI's role in the implementation of the National Solar Mission and the government's efforts to reduce risks and bring down tariffs in the solar and wind power sector. The guidelines for the tariff-based competitive bidding process are also outlined.\n\nThe process of selecting successful bidders is discussed, indicating that power will be sold to the Punjab State Power Corporation Limited (PSPCL) on a back-to-back basis. Bidders are encouraged to avail fiscal incentives for their renewable energy projects, and those who have already commissioned or are constructing projects may be given a longer period of Power Purchase Agreement (PPA). The bidding procedure is explained as a Single Stage, Two-Envelope Bidding Procedure, and interested bidders must register on the ISN-ETS portal.\n\nThe document also provides instructions for obtaining further information and emphasizes the importance of properly uploading bids on the Electronic Tendering System (ETS) portal. It states that RfS documents can be downloaded from the ETS portal or SECI's website and that any amendments or clarifications will be uploaded on the ETS website. SECI reserves the right to cancel or withdraw the invitation for bids without providing a reason.\n\nLastly, the document includes interpretations of terms and phrases used in the agreement. It clarifies the meaning of singular and plural forms, applicable laws, time of day, interpretation of different parts of the contract, and the purpose of the table of contents and headings.\n\nOverall, the first 10 pages of the document provide comprehensive information about the regulations, fees, bidding process, and contact details for the Request for Selection (RfS) for the supply of 1000 MW of firm and dispatchable power from ISTS-connected renewable energy projects in India."

